<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="2" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[192,1440,1389,1449]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,324,1389,1415]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Etymology.</emphasis>
I dedicate this species to the late Michael C. Thomas, in recognition of his many contributions to the systematics of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[353,480,1423,1449]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Coleoptera</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="2" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[192,1441,1464,1525]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,346,1464,1490]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Distribution.</emphasis>
The new species is known from 
<collectingRegion box="[716,890,1464,1491]" country="Mexico" name="San Luis Potosi" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">San Luis Potosí</collectingRegion>
, on the Atlantic versant of north central 
<collectingCountry box="[1351,1436,1464,1490]" name="Mexico" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[241,339,1498,1524]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">holotype</typeStatus>
was collected in June.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="2" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[192,1441,1539,1801]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,316,1539,1565]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rifkind" authorityYear="2020" box="[323,550,1540,1566]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thomasi">
<emphasis box="[323,550,1540,1566]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Aphelocerus thomasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from congeners by a unique combination of color pattern and elytral shape. Most 
<taxonomicName box="[457,675,1573,1599]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[457,590,1573,1599]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Aphelocerus</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
are uniformly black. Of the few bicolorous species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rifkind" authorityYear="2020" box="[1252,1371,1573,1600]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thomasi">
<emphasis box="[1252,1270,1574,1600]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1283,1371,1573,1599]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">thomasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could only be confused with the similarly sized 
<taxonomicName authority="(Barr)" baseAuthorityName="Barr" box="[651,876,1607,1633]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="delicatulus">
<emphasis box="[651,670,1607,1633]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[683,800,1607,1633]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">delicatulus</emphasis>
(Barr)
</taxonomicName>
, but the latter has the head and prothorax partially testaceous, the anterior 2/3 of the elytra with a broad longitudinal dark band at the suture, and the elytral apices distinctly more rounded than the former (
<figureCitation box="[666,731,1674,1700]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="4.[574,650,921,947]" captionTargetBox="[575,1058,213,891]" captionTargetId="figure-92@4.[574,1058,211,891]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 3. Aphelocerus delicatulus, habitus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353864" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353864/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Furthermore, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rifkind" authorityYear="2020" box="[910,1029,1674,1701]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thomasi">
<emphasis box="[910,928,1674,1700]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[941,1029,1674,1700]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">thomasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from a specimen collected in June on Mexico’s Atlantic side, whereas 
<taxonomicName box="[686,837,1708,1734]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="delicatulus">
<emphasis box="[686,705,1708,1734]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[720,837,1708,1734]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">delicatulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has only been recorded from the Pacific versant (in the states of 
<collectingRegion box="[334,418,1741,1767]" country="Mexico" name="Sinaloa" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Sinaloa</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[431,505,1741,1767]" country="Mexico" name="Jalisco" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Jalisco</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[516,601,1741,1767]" country="Mexico" name="Colima" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Colima</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[613,707,1741,1767]" country="Mexico" name="Morelos" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Morelos</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[719,795,1741,1767]" country="Mexico" name="Puebla" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Puebla</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[853,940,1741,1767]" country="Mexico" name="Oaxaca" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Oaxaca</collectingRegion>
), with all collections made from late August through October. The two species therefore appear to be both allopatric and phenologically isolated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
